Of course, that’s not why I’m here, you know. You see, there is a very specific sort of vampire that I deal with. One that’s stricter than most others due to its connection to the harvest moon, though its exact nature is hard to define. A harvest moon is not a normal moon; there’s only the phase when it reaches its height, and when it’s in that state it becomes completely dark, with only the faintest traces of its influence visible in the weather. Those few others that come closer to it during its time in the solar year are striking out against the backdrop of the lunar eclipse, making mysterious moonwalkers that can read minds, or feeding the nascent darkness with fear, or fear of darknesses that can’t quite get the strength to stand up, scratching at the edges of our protective covering. A harvest moon is a very bad sign indeed.

But Vlad doesn’t get to do that, because he’s not the one that gets to sign these things. We all understand that this is a big job, this is a big life, and by the time he’s ready, there’s not much more he can do. The bodies he takes have a limit on what they can do, and even if he beats them senseless, at what point does that actually make him stronger?

I think that’s actually one of the reasons I’ve always found him so interesting. Because, even though most of these strange impulses that feed into the vampire seem to have a logical explanation, sometimes they don’t. There was one moment, just a few months ago, that I actually thought he’d killed someone. I mean, I knew it was impossible.

