And here, at last, I saw the end of it. Phil’s eyes met mine, and I knew, as I had so often suspected, that he was simply afraid of being picked. A cowardice so acute that I could never truly know where he found himself, but a stubbornness so great that I could never fully bring myself to abandon him. In his eyes, I saw myself selected as one of his chosen ones. Chosen because I would never stop him, and, if I lived up to his demands, I had no other choice but to continue my resistance.
In the years that followed, I tried to convince myself that I was simply chosen because I would be easier to control, whereas in reality I was eager to kill to end the suffering I was now certain I was causing. Only in those rare encounters with those inhuman figures whose will I could not doubt, and whose suffering I could not begin to understand, did I begin to realize the futility of my situation.
Eventually, I was forced to abandon my plan, and retreat to the lodestone I kept close to. I took what I could of what I could of the old gnostic temple, and hurled it into the lake, the last remaining object of the hopeless faith. I waited there, for a week, but he returned no-one except his own body.
I wasn’t ready to celebrate, though, and I think in my heart he was waiting for some grand cosmic shock, to shake me free of my helplessness and despair. And when that didn’t happen, he caved and let me stay. I clung to him, weighed him down, and finally made the decision to abandon my project. To abandon my Himalayan dream.
Statement ends.
