The Tibetan Book of the Dead was published in Tibet by Longjing Publishing House in 1927, and stood in stark contrast to the Buddhist texts that dominated the literature during the Yuan dynasty. From what I can tell, there are few details in the account that match the historical account of the extinction of the Buddhino-Tibetan boundary, but a number of artifacts associated with the construction of tombs at the site have been found within the walls of the Forbidden City, most notably a piece of an ivory staff the size of a fist, and a helmet similar to that of the Sumerian god Demeter.
