I knew my old guard would have been there, but he didn’t deserve to be sacked like that. It was clear something was wrong with Grant, and I started to feel very uneasy. Was he coming back someday? He didn’t seem to know what was going on. Was I going to be safe inside the Institute, or was I just going to be safe in my bed? There was a nagging apprehension in my mind, something that after three hours I just couldn’t name. But I didn’t care. I just waited.

At some point Ikai came to check on me. Apparently there’d been some problems with the door, and I was being followed. I tried to tell him to go away, but the anger seemed to wash over me, and I shouted for him to go back, but he just stood there, confidently, like he hadn’t noticed that a while ago. The freshness of the air in the small office made me feel well rested, even though there was still that nagging apprehension in my mind.

I turned in to find Grant stood in the corner of the small doorway, looking at me with a bored expression and making some final checks on the door. It was unlocked, but I was still sure I could find something to be alarmed about. I saw the thin, sharp knife in his hand and I suddenly came to the decision that I was not going to just stand there and wait for this. I walked over, planted myself across from him, and grabbed him by the collar of his shirt.

