That’s not to say I didn’t worry. I did worry. But, before the second semester finished, I asked Ethan if he knew of any help or places to look for answers to his delayed questions.
He gave me a sheepish smile, and returned to checking his watch minutes before the exam began. I noticed that the flashlight he had brought was heavier than I would have expected, but I wasn’t particularly troubled by it. Ethan had always been picky about where he went off the grid, and I had no idea where he had hidden these caches.
Still, it was a cold night in December, and the first thing I worried about Ethan was the clocks. I had kept my nightly vigil lower than I had ever done in the nights since my return, and the nights had not been this way for some months. I had done my best to discourage him from going to bed early, but it was still an every-other-week ritual.
Ethan had always been picky about where he went to sleep. Even before he told me his secrets, I could count the minutes until I heard that heavy tread outside the door, and had known that creeping nightmare for so long I could no longer be sure where to go in the dark.
So I waited. I had been faithful to the Light of Deliverance only for the sake of my students, and to my dying day, I would have sworn that my preaching surpassed the powers of darkness in that hour and a half. And I stood before the altar, straining my preaching hand until I had touched it, and heard the voice of my Saviour, shouting, “Come, Lord Jesus, be our salvation!” But the tongue that reached my mouth was words, hollow and waved in the darkest corners of the universe, and as I uttered the name “Blessedness,” I felt my own salvation begin to flow out and bubble up out of me.
In the end, I put the hour of my death before the service at the altar. I would have finished the service, if not for the dire shortage of alcohol I had encountered in the hours before. I stumbled, and my bones were broken, but I remember that shift count was not something I thought about until just now.
