Statement of Elias Bouchard, aka Dr. Pritchard, regarding the night of 23rd January, 2006. Original statement given February 14th, 2007. Audio recording by Jonathan Sims, The Archivist.

Statement begins.

ARCHIVIST (STATEMENT)
You don’t need me to tell you what a day studying anatomy is. I’ll call it what it is, and you’ll have to read an account of how it became a thing.

But let me tell you what it isn’t. It isn’t a statement. It isn’t a vision. It isn’t a ghost. Because what it is is blood. And needles and gangrene and itch. That’s what it is. That’s what we put patients through, to tell you what it is.

You don’t need needles or gangrene or itch. What it is is is vulnerability. Isolated, raw, sometimes dangerous, but it is not what leads to outbreaks of infection. Corridors; panic; panic; sometimes it’s just the lack of structure that lets people suffer such a fate.

I was on a boat for two days. No doctor or hospital, no testing, no appointments. We had just touched on the second largest outbreak of disease in human history, as many as six million people, half of them children, who faced death within a few months. It was a gruesome way to look at things, but it was the only way to make sure that nothing was going to go in there.

There was a boat there, headed towards the Galápagos, a tiny island off the mainland. It shouldn’t have been that, but looking at it, I couldn’t help but notice the stenciled names on the side: Diego Molina, Diego Molina, Diego Molina. I don’t know the others. I hope not.

There was nothing on it, but… when the water was high enough that you could see the stars through the dark clouds, far off in the distance. One of the children’s smiles was the same. A quick, jerky motion, like a vice squeezing the hand away from your face.

As it made its arduous way across the ocean, I watched it for a long time. It seemed to be completely alone.

Then it moved, slowly, but clearly, and I realised what I was looking at.

It was when I came close to falling off my seat that I felt something. I didn’t cry, just sat there, metal bars embedded in my flesh, waiting to fall off.

I don’t remember much more of what I felt than the occasional flare of sunflower, a spindly friday, a hint of iron and a splash of red.

As the day wore on, the tension in my loins disappeared, and soon I was sleeping peacefully beside Diego.

