Statement of Antonia Haley, regarding a… strange computer program she downloaded from the Deep Web three months ago.

Original statement given March 31st, 2014. Audio recording by Jonathan Sims, head archivist of the Magnus Institute, London.

Statement begins.

ARCHIVIST (STATEMENT)
Okay, I know how it looks like from a copyright standpoint, but if you just look at the claim of infringement, then yes. The- uh, the first time it appeared on my computer was when I was nine. I got into a fight in school, and nobody was hurt. It was after having spilled milk on a friend of mine; she had it streaming down her throat. And I watched, transfixed by that featureless face of her, staring back at me. In the background, I could see a spider. I think it was the first time there had been a spider that I’d seen since we were children.

Since then, I used to spend a lot of time outside, and I would spend long afternoons hunting for hidden webs. I was often not sure exactly what I was looking for, but I would spend a lot of time just sat there, watching the web that grew and spread out of the corners of the garden. I must have looked after the house for a good ten or eleven years straight.

Obviously, the webbing went out after that. I don’t know how precisely I knew it was going to stop, but once or twice I think it got stuck. I could always see it in the sunlight, stretching away into the blue sky, or the dark, swirling clouds above the city.

I could never figure out what it was, or where, but it always looked to be coming towards me, and I could never get close enough. Looking back, it looks like that was the point: that moment I was, I decided to run. I didn’t turn around, nor do I have any other plans, so when the webs were dragged across the floor and caught I decided I was running.

I’m sure you can guess the plan. I got in through the front door. I knocked on the door and it opened. There were no lights on inside, and the place was utterly silent, but my fear didn’t let me relax. There was no safe, or a key, or… Package! I got as far as the drawers and slid inside.

My parents were very alarmed by this. They Uncaged me a bit and started to push me out of the door. What did you expect? Did they know something I didn’t? Could they have predicted this would happen? I didn’t really have anything to say to this, so I just nodded, got out of the car, and began to cover the door. Once I had got a look inside, they were both quiet. They stared at me for a long moment, but then they started to walk up towards the door, and I realised there was a presence in the house. It was still, but it seemed to move. It was ever so slightly closer. I slowly crept towards it, but my mind was aflame with fear. I didn’t want to get inside.

This pleading did nothing to quell the fear that had settled over me, and I pressed on. My hands began to grow wet with what I assumed, at the time, was sweat, and I started to shiver in what I can only assume was disgust. As I reached the second step up the stairs, I gripped the handle and moved it back down. I felt something soft and wet against the wood of the floor. I pulled my hand out and instinctively I gripped it. By chance I felt a small, ragged hole in the side of my shoe.

I don’t know what I expected. Maybe I thought this would be the end of the story, and I was wrong. But what else could I expect from a book that claimed to tell its story? I pressed on, still no speaker heard me, and the story just kept going. The wall was reeking of ozone, and the subject was still her, still puzzling and misfiling. After a half hour I had almost written myself off. Except that now it didn’t feel so hopeless. I began to feel that I might have found a way to leave, and I did. I

