I came into work yesterday to find a box sat on my desk. The address and label had been completely scribbled over in black marker pen, and it was impossible to tell from where exactly I got it. It wasn’t from India, though, or Tibet, or anywhere else in the world. It looked like the address had been written over in English, though, so I don’t necessarily think it was from any of the places listed.

I was going to phone the police, but then I heard Katy’s laughter, just above my head. She said that they’d received a call and were on the way to the address included in the letter. They were questioning a man who they said had confessed to embezzling money from the company. The man, she said, was a suspect in a string of serious crimes, and she was sure he was the same.

Obviously I was skeptical, and I asked Miss Prentiss if there was any way the police could get involved. She told me that there was nothing they could do, that there was no evidence to suggest the man had committed any crimes. Clearly there was no evidence, and I should have got a lawyer, but I was under no obligation to pay anyone a visit. I was just getting a bit excited.

Then Katy got up and left, closing the door behind her. I can’t stress that enough. I could fall asleep, they said. Just don’t do it.

I called the police again. They came in to question the man, but he was already dead. The autopsy showed carbon monoxide poisoning, due to a short-circuit, but it didn’t seem to show signs of violence, or any sort of mutilation, so I assumed it must have been natural. The police checked his death, and confirmed that it didn’t appear to involve any illegal activity, and that’s all the information I was ever able to get from the police.

It’s weird, right? You’re all set to dood it up, put music and light into people’s basements, when they’re not even there. I mean, they took the body down, and started to disinfect it, but aside from a few police reports, there’s not been anything there from a decade.

Obviously people get suspicious when they find out their neighbours are always watchful. I didn’t believe it, at least not until I got the call about his final project. I don’t know how it suddenly became the focus of a Murdocook documentary.

It was a short film, by some pseudointellectual called Nikola Tesla. It’s still somehow relevant, even though the events themselves haven’t been demonstrably connected. But it was titled “The Prescription Man”, and while the film itself has nothing to do with Nikola Tesla, the prescient statements and findings seem to tie in with recent events.

So, I had a small meeting with Niko, and a few other temporary staff. They were trying to organise an exhibition of his work, while I got to work on his computer. None of the people I brought in, or the people I hired, have returned to work on the Mauritsen research team, with the exception of one or two post-grad students.

I wanted to keep the footage I had, for obvious reasons, and was worried about the legality of the footage. But I also realised that it was going to be monitored. I can’t take full advantage of the space, but I figured it wouldn’t be long until the students were back inside, so I gave Dana another description of the situation.

She didn’t seem particularly worried, just looked over and nodded. It was technically legal, but she pressed me again to turn it off. I explained to her that I’d only given it as a last resort, and if there was anything you care to do about it, I’m all ears.

She nodded, though, so I guess she didn’t really know what I was talking about. I reminded her that she’d need to talk to a manager, or something, but she didn’t seem really taken care of by them. I reminded her of the fine print on my provisional permit, and she handed me her lease and then left.

